---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import Newsletter from '../components/Newsletter.astro';
---

<Base
  title="Mind — Psychological Sovereignty"
  description="The Mind pillar at AfterChildren. Purpose after the kids leave, marriage reset, friendship reconstruction, cognitive maintenance, loneliness, therapy. The interior architecture of the second half — built on purpose, not by default."
>
  <!-- PILLAR HERO -->
  <section class="page">
    <div class="pillar-hero">
      <p class="pillar-hero__eyebrow">Sovereignty 03</p>
      <h1 class="pillar-hero__title">
        Mind.<br />
        <em>The architecture that holds the meaning.</em>
      </h1>
      <p class="pillar-hero__lede">
        For thirty years your psychological architecture was held up by the children. Their needs structured your day. Their problems gave you something to solve. Their futures gave you something to plan for. Now they are gone. What remains is a marriage that has not been examined in a decade, a friendship circle that has been quietly thinning, and a cognitive infrastructure that nobody warned you needs maintenance. The mind you build in the second half is not the mind you ended the first half with. It has to be built deliberately. Almost nobody does this work, which is why almost everyone gets blindsided by it.
      </p>
      <div class="pillar-hero__meta">
        <span><span class="pillar-hero__count">22</span> planned articles in this pillar</span>
        <span class="pillar-hero__sep">·</span>
        <span><span class="pillar-hero__count">0</span> live now</span>
        <span class="pillar-hero__sep">·</span>
        <span>First article: the loneliness essay</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- WHERE TO START -->
  <section class="page">
    <div class="start-panel">
      <p class="start-panel__eyebrow">Where to start</p>
      <h2 class="start-panel__title">Three moves. This quarter. Before the drift sets in.</h2>
      <ol class="start-panel__list">
        <li class="start-panel__item">
          <span class="start-panel__num">01</span>
          <div>
            <h3 class="start-panel__step">Name the next thing</h3>
            <p class="start-panel__desc">Not a hobby. A project that will absorb 8 to 15 hours of your week for the next 5 to 10 years, has a measurable shape, and exists for reasons other than the kids. Most parents who fail at this stage failed because they expected the answer to arrive. It does not arrive. You name it, badly, and refine it later. The naming is the work.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="start-panel__item">
          <span class="start-panel__num">02</span>
          <div>
            <h3 class="start-panel__step">Schedule the marriage conversation</h3>
            <p class="start-panel__desc">A weekend away. No phones. No grandchildren. The agenda: what do we want the next 25 years to look like, and are we both still in. Most empty-nest marriages have never had this conversation. The ones that do not have it are the ones that quietly dissolve at 67. The ones that do have it tend to survive and improve. The cost is one weekend. The downside is finding out what is true.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="start-panel__item">
          <span class="start-panel__num">03</span>
          <div>
            <h3 class="start-panel__step">Reach out to one dormant friend</h3>
            <p class="start-panel__desc">Someone who mattered to you 10 to 30 years ago and you have not spoken to in over a year. One message. No agenda. "I was thinking about you." Friendships in the second half are not built. They are reactivated. The people who reactivate three of these per year have full social calendars by 70. The people who do not are quietly alone by 75.</p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FEATURED MANIFESTO -->
  <section class="page">
    <div class="featured">
      <p class="featured__eyebrow">Start here</p>
      <a href="#" class="featured__card" style="opacity: 0.85;">
        <div class="featured__meta">
          <span class="featured__tag">Coming Soon</span>
          <span class="featured__time">Manifesto · ~14 min read</span>
        </div>
        <h2 class="featured__title">The Loneliness After Kids Leave Is Real — And Solvable.</h2>
        <p class="featured__excerpt">Why the year after the last child leaves is statistically the loneliest year of most parents' adult lives. The neurological basis, the social structure that produces it, and the deliberate work that fixes it. The fourth and final manifesto in the founding cluster — ships next week.</p>
        <span class="featured__cta">Subscribe to the Sunday Letter to get it first <span class="featured__arrow">→</span></span>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- THE SIX MIND SUB-PILLARS -->
  <section class="page">
    <div class="subpillars">
      <p class="subpillars__eyebrow">The six mind domains</p>
      <h2 class="subpillars__title">The psychological sovereignty work, broken down.</h2>

      <div class="subpillar">
        <div class="subpillar__head">
          <span class="subpillar__num">01</span>
          <h3 class="subpillar__title">Purpose after parenting</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="subpillar__intro">For three decades your central project was raising another human. The project ended on a Tuesday afternoon when the last car pulled out of the driveway. The wellness industry will tell you to discover your passion. That advice is useless because passion is not the right unit. The right unit is a project with shape, duration, and measurable progress. Most parents who flourish in the second half have one or two such projects. Most who decline do not. The work is to name yours, build the scaffolding, and accept that the early version will be wrong.</p>
        <ul class="subpillar__list">
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The Empty Nest Identity Problem (And the Six-Month Window)</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Finding Purpose After 55: Why "Find Your Passion" Is Bad Advice</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The Encore Career: When It Works, When It Doesn't</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Volunteering as Structure: Choosing Well</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The Solo Project Test: Can You Tolerate Working Without an Audience?</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="subpillar">
        <div class="subpillar__head">
          <span class="subpillar__num">02</span>
          <h3 class="subpillar__title">Marriage reset</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="subpillar__intro">The marriage that raised the children is not the marriage that will see you through the next thirty years. The roles have changed. The shared project has ended. The time alone together — for the first time in twenty-five years — is suddenly unstructured. Gray divorce has doubled since 1990, and the steepest rise is in the first three years after the last child leaves. Most of those divorces were avoidable. The ones that survive almost always did the same thing: they treated the post-children marriage as a new marriage and renegotiated it deliberately. The ones that didn't, drifted.</p>
        <ul class="subpillar__list">
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The Empty Nest Marriage: It's a New Relationship, Not the Same One</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Gray Divorce: Why It Spikes at 55, and What to Do About It</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The Weekend Away Conversation: What to Actually Discuss</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> When Therapy Helps a Long Marriage (And When It Doesn't)</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Sex and Intimacy in the Second Half: The Conversation Nobody Has</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="subpillar">
        <div class="subpillar__head">
          <span class="subpillar__num">03</span>
          <h3 class="subpillar__title">Friendship reconstruction</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="subpillar__intro">Friendships in your 50s and 60s decay faster than they did in your 30s. The shared activities that maintained them — work, parenting logistics, neighborhood overlap — disappear. Men lose friends faster than women, and by 65, the average man has fewer than three people he would call in a crisis. The fix is not making new friends. Making new friends is hard at 60 and produces shallow results. The fix is reactivating dormant friendships from earlier decades. The data on this is overwhelming and almost completely unused. Most reactivations succeed. Most parents never attempt one.</p>
        <ul class="subpillar__list">
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Reactivating Dormant Friendships: The Highest-ROI Social Move After 55</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Why Men Lose Friends Faster (And the Fix)</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Making New Friends After 60: When It Works</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The Six-Person Rule: How Many Close Friends You Actually Need</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="subpillar">
        <div class="subpillar__head">
          <span class="subpillar__num">04</span>
          <h3 class="subpillar__title">Cognitive maintenance</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="subpillar__intro">The brain-training industry generated $8 billion in 2024 selling apps that, in the peer-reviewed evidence, do almost nothing. The actual interventions that delay cognitive decline — exercise, sleep, social engagement, hearing aids, treating hypertension, treating depression, reading challenging material — are mostly free, mostly known, and mostly ignored. About 40% of dementia cases trace to modifiable risk factors. The work is identifying which ones apply to you and addressing them in your 50s and 60s, not your 70s when the window has narrowed.</p>
        <ul class="subpillar__list">
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Cognitive Decline: The 40% That Is Modifiable</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Brain-Training Apps: Why the Evidence Doesn't Support the Marketing</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The Hearing Loss / Dementia Connection</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Reading, Learning, and Cognitive Reserve</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> When to Get a Baseline Cognitive Assessment</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="subpillar">
        <div class="subpillar__head">
          <span class="subpillar__num">05</span>
          <h3 class="subpillar__title">Loneliness &amp; social structure</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="subpillar__intro">The U.S. Surgeon General declared loneliness a public health crisis in 2023. The mortality cost is comparable to smoking 15 cigarettes a day. The demographic with the steepest rise is parents in the first three years after the last child leaves. Loneliness is not solved by feeling less lonely. It is solved by structural changes to your week — recurring commitments, regular contact, embedded community. The interventions are simple. The discipline to install them, before the loneliness becomes chronic, is not.</p>
        <ul class="subpillar__list">
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> The Loneliness Epidemic After 55: The Numbers</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Structural Loneliness Solutions: What Actually Works</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Recurring Commitments: The Quiet Weapon Against Isolation</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Why Religious Communities Outperform on Aging Outcomes (Even for Non-Believers)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="subpillar">
        <div class="subpillar__head">
          <span class="subpillar__num">06</span>
          <h3 class="subpillar__title">Therapy &amp; mental health</h3>
        </div>
        <p class="subpillar__intro">Depression in adults over 55 is under-diagnosed, under-treated, and over-medicated. About 1 in 7 adults over 60 meets criteria for major depression, but fewer than half receive evidence-based treatment. The cultural barriers are real — this generation was raised to not discuss it — but the consequences of not addressing it are worse than the discomfort of starting. Therapy works. SSRIs work for the right cases. The combination usually works better than either alone. The question is not whether to seek help. The question is how to find a competent provider in a market with low standards.</p>
        <ul class="subpillar__list">
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Depression After 55: The Symptoms That Look Like Aging</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Finding a Therapist Who Works With Older Adults</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Antidepressants in the Second Half: What the Evidence Says</li>
          <li><span class="subpillar__soon">Coming</span> Anxiety and Health Anxiety in the Aging Body</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- COMMITMENTS -->
  <section class="page">
    <div class="commitments">
      <p class="commitments__eyebrow">Our mind-content rules</p>
      <h2 class="commitments__title">What we promise on every psychological page.</h2>
      <div class="commitments__grid">
        <div class="commitment">
          <h3 class="commitment__title">No wellness-industry hedging</h3>
          <p class="commitment__desc">We do not say "consider exploring" when the evidence supports a direct recommendation. We do not call therapy "self-care." We do not soften research findings to avoid making the reader uncomfortable. Mind content on this site is direct, specific, and respects your ability to handle the truth about your own life.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="commitment">
          <h3 class="commitment__title">Not therapy</h3>
          <p class="commitment__desc">Articles on this site are independent journalism, not clinical treatment. If you are in mental health crisis, the right tool is a licensed clinician, not an essay. We cite the research. We name the protocols. We tell you when something is an opinion and when it is evidence. We do not replace the therapist you may need.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="commitment">
          <h3 class="commitment__title">Evidence over story</h3>
          <p class="commitment__desc">Mind topics attract anecdote, memoir, and storytelling. We use stories sparingly, and only to illustrate a finding the research already supports. The data leads. The story follows. We do not publish "my journey" essays as if one person's experience were a guide for yours.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="commitment">
          <h3 class="commitment__title">Reviewer layer (rolling out)</h3>
          <p class="commitment__desc">Articles on mental health, therapy, and clinical conditions will progressively carry a "Reviewed by [Name, Credential]" line as we bring on credentialed reviewers — a clinical psychologist for therapy content, a geriatric psychiatrist for medication-related material, a researcher for cognitive content. Until then, articles in this section are bylined by M. Holloway, the founder, or the AfterChildren Editorial Desk.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- AFFILIATES -->
  <section class="page">
    <div class="affiliates">
      <p class="affiliates__eyebrow">Affiliate disclosure</p>
      <h2 class="affiliates__title">What we link to, and what we earn.</h2>
      <p class="affiliates__intro">When we recommend a service, we link to it. When the link earns us a commission, we disclose it. We are particularly careful in this pillar — mental health services have a long history of bad actors, and we will not link to anything that does not meet a clear competence bar.</p>
      <p class="affiliates__intro affiliates__intro--secondary">As this pillar develops, the partner list below will become live affiliate links. Until then, the list documents the categories we are evaluating. Each gets a published review before any link goes live.</p>
      <div class="affiliates__list">
        <div class="affiliate">
          <h4 class="affiliate__name">Therapy &amp; counseling</h4>
          <p class="affiliate__desc">Therapist directories and platforms with licensed providers, transparent pricing, and credible matching. Under evaluation: Psychology Today directory (free), Alma, Grow Therapy, Open Path Collective for sliding scale.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="affiliate">
          <h4 class="affiliate__name">Marriage &amp; couples therapy</h4>
          <p class="affiliate__desc">Evidence-based modalities (Gottman, EFT) with verified credentials. Under evaluation: Gottman Referral Network, ICEEFT, The Couples Center.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="affiliate">
          <h4 class="affiliate__name">Cognitive-behavioral self-guided programs</h4>
          <p class="affiliate__desc">For the subset of cases where structured digital programs are evidence-backed. Under evaluation: SilverCloud Health, Woebot (for anxiety), MoodGYM.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="affiliate">
          <h4 class="affiliate__name">Meditation &amp; cognitive training</h4>
          <p class="affiliate__desc">The few apps with peer-reviewed evidence behind them. Under evaluation: Healthy Minds Program, Waking Up. We will not link to brain-training apps that lack supporting evidence.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="affiliate">
          <h4 class="affiliate__name">Journaling &amp; reflection tools</h4>
          <p class="affiliate__desc">Physical journals and digital tools that hold up to consistent use. Under evaluation: Leuchtturm1917, Moleskine, Day One app.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="affiliate">
          <h4 class="affiliate__name">Books &amp; recommended reading</h4>
          <p class="affiliate__desc">Curated essential reading on purpose, marriage, friendship, and cognition for the second half. Bookshop.org affiliate link supports independent bookstores. Amazon links secondary.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA: ASK A QUESTION -->
  <section class="page">
    <div class="ask">
      <h2 class="ask__title">A mind question we should answer?</h2>
      <p class="ask__lede">If a Mind topic is on your mind and not on the list above, send it. We read everything. We do not respond individually, but the most-asked questions become next month's articles.</p>
      <p class="ask__contact">Write to <a href="mailto:editor@afterchildren.com">editor@afterchildren.com</a> with subject line "Mind: [topic]".</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <Newsletter />
</Base>

